                                                                                                5.3.4, respectively), after which the symmetric key is used to encrypt files or messages or
                                                                                                to distribute other keys.
                                                                                                In some situations, asymmetric-key cryptography is not necessary, and symmetric-key
                                                                                                cryptography alone is sufficient. This includes environments where secure symmetric-key
                                                                                                establishment can take place using symmetric keys already shared between entities,
                                                                                                environments where a single authority knows and manages all the keys, and in single-user
                                                                                                environments.
                                                                                                In general, asymmetric-key cryptography is best suited for an open, multi-user
                                                                                                environment. However, with the impending availability of quantum computing, the current
                                                                                                asymmetric algorithms will become vulnerable to attacks (see the note in Section 3.3).
